TY  - JOUR
T1  - Temporary, Emergent Interorganizational Collaboration in Unexpected Circumstances: A Study of the Columbia Space Shuttle Response Effort
AU  - Beck, Tammy E.
AU  - Plowman, Donde Ashmos
Y1  - 2013/12/23
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2014/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2013.0888
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2013.0888
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 1234
EP  - 1252
VL  - 25
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In an inductive case study of the Columbia space shuttle disaster response effort, we use observations, archival records, and in-depth interviews with representatives from several responding agencies to explore factors that facilitated this interorganizational collaboration. The Columbia response effort defies conventional theories of collaboration. Relative strangers from dissimilar agencies, without a designated leader or existing structure, quickly collaborated across organizational boundaries on an unprecedented and complex undertaking. We explain how four organizing actions enabled self-organizing and the two-staged development of trust and identity, ultimately leading to a successful unplanned collaboration. We rely on tenets of complexity theory to orient our case study and to propose a grounded theory of temporary, emergent interorganizational collaboration.
